The drawer slid open with a soft, protesting groan of aged wood, revealing a meticulous array of linen and cufflinks. Yet, tucked beneath a stack of freshly laundered handkerchiefs, almost too carefully concealed, lay a single sheet of heavy cream paper. It was a ledger page, its crisp, hand-ruled columns filled with an urgent, looping script detailing sums that would make a nabob blush, each entry a stark testament to ruinous gambling debts that stretched far beyond any reasonable inheritance. The air within the drawer held a faint scent of lavender and old paper, a secret undoubtedly, and one that demanded further scrutiny of young Julian Thorne.

